Yi Peng is a must on any travellers bucket list. This beautiful festival is celebrated across Thailand on the full moon of November but for the best views head to Chiang Mai where the largest release of lanterns takes place! There are both private and public celebrations for releasing lanterns, if you want a big setup release such as the one captured in this video you will need to cough up over $100 and travel out to the festival grounds 45 minutes outside the city. If this doesn’t fit your backpacker budget then no worries, there are plenty of free festivals all around that just aren’t as coordinated. No matter where you go though, this is a festival you can’t miss just make sure to follow local guidelines and only release lanterns in spaces that have been approved for it. Happy traveling!
.

Here’s a little comparison between one of my favourite memories this year and the photo I took in the same spot 2 years prior. Definitely have had a hard year with being proud of my photography but looking back can be a good reminder that progress has been made and that’s all that matters. If works been done then be proud of it!

Memories from this early October morning hike to larch valley. This has to be one of the most captivating and rewarding hikes in Canada. After an hour of non stop uphill switch backs the forest opens up into a maze of beautiful bright orange foliage surround by towering rocky peaks. The colours feel surreal like you’ve discovered natures art exhibit. Save this and add larch valley to your list of places to visit next fall!

I posted a photo of this mountain a few days ago and you guys seemed to really like it so I thought I would share a few other angles I took while trying to capture this incredible scene. There’s endless ways of taking the “same photo” it’s up to you to add your own secret spices that make the moment unique. Being unique seems difficult as a photographer these days now that everyone has a camera but instead of trying to be different from everyone else, I try to be unique from my own photos. It’s a healthier way to stay competitive without falling into the trap of comparing yourself to others. Strive to be better than your previous self not someone else, the rest will come consequently. I don’t even know if that makes sense but we are going with it 👍🏼

Hope everyone has been enjoying the holidays! @zoeakiko and I have been working hard as 2023 approaches, to figure out what next year will look like for us. It feels like there are too many paths that we could take and we would love to hear if you have any ideas or preferences for the content you would like to see. International travel, long road trips, photography here in B.C, more info based tutorials, anything! Let me know!
I know the fall photos are out of date but the feed is gonna be beautiful. Trust me
Here’s your yearly photo of me. In 2023 I’m going to try and share more about myself and will share more photos that @zoeakiko takes of me.

Open fields + sunset = easy dreamy photo shoots. Pulled over to the side of the highway for this 2 minute impromptu photoshoot. It seems to be the spontaneous photoshoots that become the most memorable. You never regret pulling over when you feel inspired, you only ever regret driving past.
Missing van life but I definitely enjoy turning on our car without a mechanic on speed dial.
One of those run around in an empty field type days

I think this made for a really interesting perspective and an insightful look at our human instinct to stick together (other than this one guy guess💁🏽‍♂️).

Continuing with another little Egypt throw back, here’s a view of the famous pyramids that had been on my bucket list since I was a child. So fortunate to have visited without nearly any other tourists around. The only other people there ended up looking nice in the photo anyways 🤷🏽‍♂️

23 years old today :) this is the first year that there’s no new Taylor swift song about your age and no new things you are allowed to do. Got kinda sad thinking about that until I realized 23 and the years to follow are the years you start to make ur own experiences out of life. I no longer need a song or a law to tell me what to do or explore this year; I can just make my own story for my 23rd year here. Here are some of this past years many highlights.
1. Exploring Cambodia with @lexielimitless 
2. Summer beach nights with @zoeakiko @lil_niki @justin.choquette @em.ksmith
3. Going out in Toronto with the @canoncanada futures squad
4. Adventuring through San Josef bay with my best friends
5. @zoeakiko birthday bike ride through Stanley park
6. The streets of Europe with @lexielimitless
7. Exploring the beaches of Baja California with my Mexican familia / life long friends
8. Vanlife adventures with my ❤️
9. Rooftops of Toronto with @lifeofstfphen 
10.	A Van life getaway with @brynnsadventures and @oliver.castle 
Thank you to everyone who made the 22nd chapter of my life so special

These might be my favourite shots from my trip to Cambodia. Loved learning some Khmer (Cambodias official language) and trying it out on the monks who we met at these temples. The first thing I learn to say in any new country is “can I take your photo” and it sure paid off here. Let me know if you wanna see more from the monks of Cambodia! Got lots more where this came from.

If Cambodia isn’t on your travel bucket list yet then add it now. Seriously such a gem to explore this beautiful country and discover the countless ancient temples buried beneath the jungle. Love how nature has reclaimed these buildings over hundreds if not thousands of years. I dream of one day discovering something lost in time, I can’t imagine the feeling of cutting through the jungle and discovering a site like this that’s been unseen for ages.

For the record I have over 100 photo posts I’ve been procrastinating sharing because they are a few months old and I don’t want to confuse people as to where I am. I’ve decided that’s enough procrastination and I gotta just start posting. My stories will be more up to date and my feed will be more about just sharing my art. Sorry y’all! Lots more like this coming your way 🙌🏼
Also @lexielimitless nailed the tomb raider vibes here!

Lost in the ancient city of Angkor Wat. You could easily get lost within this ancient city considering the whole city is estimated to have been the size of London and it housed nearly a million residents. 
This is day 2 of posting photos that aren’t take recently but I have wanted to post for months now. Hope you don’t mind 🙂

Cambodia quickly became one of my favourite countries to travel! Not only did we find stunning spots to shoot but we found this spring roll restaurant that I haven’t stopped thinking about since leaving. Seriously considering going back just for those spring rolls😫

One of my favourite parts of travel has to be connecting with locals and diving into cultures I’ve never experienced before. This is the part of travel that’s easy to skip but will surely give you the most authentic experiences.

Moments when everything aligns 🙌🏼 the greatest joy as a photographer are when everything syncs up for that 500th of a second and a subject centres themselves or the stars align. This moment was special as I had been running around this temple frantically trying to find an angle and then out of the corner of my eye I see a monk walking towards this temple entrance. I aligned myself with the door and was able to capture the second where all was in line. It’s like watching the DVD logo bounce around the screen until it hits the corner. Very satisfying

Last series from Cambodia for now! Loved these photos and this moment I shared with two local monks. I’ve got so much more to share from Cambodia but we will save it for a a future series. Where do you want to see photos from next? Europe, Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand, Canada??

Finding shade on the beaches of Raja Ampat. If there was any place to get stranded on an Island it would be here..
If you have never heard of Raja Ampat, I highly recommend u look at adding it to your bucket list. Probably the most beautiful place I have ever been and completely empty. 
Got so much more that I can’t wait to share from this trip!!

A chance to feel creative again. Its been a while since I have really exercised my creativity and this trip to Raja Ampat with friends was just that. These impromptu photo shoots on the beach are were a creative rejuvenation for me and you will be seeing a lot more of them over the next little while. Got so many more photos and videos from here.

Chasing the perfect shot under the relentless sun of Raja Ampat. Located almost directly on the equator Raja offered some of the most beautiful beaches I’ve ever seen but at the cost of burning almost instantly. SPF 30 proved no match for this photo shoot as by the end of the day I looked like a tomato.

This beach on Vancouver island was just named one of the top 50 beaches in the whole world (36th to be exact) and 2nd in all of America / Canada. 
Welcome to San Josef, this beautiful bay in the middle of the northern island wilderness blew my mind with its beauty! Blue water, perfect sand, incredible rock structures that tower throughout and a beach that goes on and on without a single other person in sight! This list Collaborated with over 750 travel influencers and professionals to rank beaches across the globe. The beaches were ranked according to five criteria: "sheer untouched nature, remoteness, how swimmable it is, annual days of sunshine, and average annual temperature” I would like to think if it wasn’t for the rainfall category, San Josef would be ranked above Mcway beach in California and would take the number one spot for North America. Makes me proud to call B.C home!

social_posts.post_text: I can’t wait to go back to Mexico again sometime soon! So blessed to know some amazing people down there who show us all the best spots. Knowing a local is by far the most underrated travel hack. It’s amazing the experiences u can get by following someone around that you trust both personally and from a knowledge standpoint.

Catching the morning sun on the Calico Jack. 
Our boat the Calico Jack was named after an English pirate born in 1682 who lived an eventful life flaunting the Jolly Roger flag on his ship. 
Reading into the history of this man while writing this post, truly feels like I’m reading the script to a pirates of the Caribbean movie. Hard to imagine what it must have been like back then for both the pirates and the pirated. It felt like as we sailed through the islands of Raja Ampat, we got a glimpse into a time before machines and modernism. I time away from phones, cities but thankfully also a time away from any pirates.

I’ve had a vision of how I would create a shoe commercial for a while now and @cascadesigns gave me the opportunity to make this come to life. Casca lets you step into another world of comfort and I wanted to capture that with this story! Always such a pleasure working with local brands based here in Vancouver and getting the opportunity to put so much creativity to a project! If you are looking for some new shoes to hit the town or forest this summer, definitely go check out what @cascadesigns has to offer!

I’m verified on Instagram now! I applied for the new meta verified program which meant I had to confirm my username was my legal name, send a photo of my passport and change my profile picture to a pic of my face that matches my ID. Kind of a weird process but I’m here for it… curious to hear your thoughts on all of this and any questions you might have! I’m actually optimistic about this shift in social media. I don’t mind paying a small amount to one or two platforms for a vastly better experience just like we used to pay for tv channels. If this cuts down on spam, harassment, fake accounts and distributes the engagement on Instagram to the original creators then I think it’s worth it to me. But if @meta happens to see this, please let us post higher quality photos and videos of we are paying you money… the compressed quality we currently have to post to / view at is outdated. Those are my takes on this! Would love to hear yours! ⬇️
.
Also isn’t @zoeakiko beautiful? 😍
Always been on the hunt for the perfect bent palm tree. Once I saw this one I knew we wouldn’t be going anywhere else for at least an hour 😅
Endless frames from Raja
This was not nearly as comfortable as it seems. Soon after laying down on this tree, @itsrubyrojas realized it was covered in fire ants… 🐜🔥

Raja Ampat on film 🎞️
There's a timeless charm to shooting on film. Every click of the shutter is a tangible moment, a blend of anticipation and permanence that digital just can't replicate. I enjoy slowing down to concentrate on every frame.
Can you tell which photos are shot on film?
Film vs digital (first shot on film, rest on digital). Here are the last few shots from this series.

As a photographer I never leave home without a camera. Travel photography can be done two ways; you can head to a location with an exact plan and vision or it can just be arriving at a random village and capturing the locals in their element. Raja Ampat is a remote series of islands that takes more than a day to get to from Bali or Jakarta. These islands hold some of the most beautiful tropical beaches in the world and a few of them are home to local kids who were so excited to meet us as we explored.

About the 99% of the time I regret bringing my gigantic 600mm lens with me everywhere as I travel as it’s brutal on my back and takes up my whole bag BUT every now and then it’s worth it and this was one of those times. Such an amazing moment being able to capture this whole family of monkeys on camera.

Came across one young monk wandering the grounds of Angkor Wat in Cambodia trying to grab the attention of some monkeys who call the ancient temple home. Another special moment to capture on camera. Innocence, fascination and child like joy that I envy.
Peaceful afternoons in the Korean countryside. Here’s your reminder to take things slow. Slow is smooth and smooth is fast. Also go outside and get some fresh air, it’s good for you 🌲

Trying out something new is refreshing… In Korea I was inspired to give off a sense of tranquility with my videos. Here is my second attempt at it (yesterdays video was the first). 😁 Let me know if you want to see more like this 🏞️🌅🏜️
Your daily reminder to take a deep breath and relax…

I always get jealous of historic photos. There’s a feeling that a photo gives when there is deep history embedded within. Photos can age like wine (most of mine have not if u scroll down on my feed) . My goal with this shot was to give that feeling despite being shot just a few months ago. As a photographer I can only dream my photos live on beyond my time. We all have the desire to leave a print in the history books and I hope one day a photo of mine does just that.

One night while down in Baja Mexico, I came across this rancher watching his land in the dark. This was another one of those uncomfortable moments where I knew I needed to go ask for a photo or I would regret it forever. A moment of both excitement as I can see a clear creative vision but also pure terror as I realize I actually have to get out the car and go ask. So glad I did because I love how it turned out! These spontaneous cultural portraits are never the flashiest of my photos but they are my favourite because they are so authentic and have a clear story behind them.

Swipe to see me 🥵 from eating spicy food… In Thailand it’s not uncommon to see markets and vendors setup shop in some wild places. From the side of train tracks to this lady who has her whole restaurant inside of this canoe. From cooking to dish cleaning she does it all from her seat along the rivers edge.  We had to stop for a meal and it was an interesting one. I ordered wonton pad Thai and I ended up with the spiciest meal of my life with 10 types of sea food I couldn’t identify. Wouldn’t have traded it for a thing… the last frame here is from @lexielimitless video she made on the whole trip to Thailand which captured my reaction to the spice perfectly😅

Creativity itself doesn't care at all about results - the only thing it craves is the process. Learn to love the process and let whatever happens next happen, without fussing too much about it. Work like a monk, or a mule, or some other representative metaphor for diligence. Love the work. Destiny will do what it wants with you, regardless.

- Elizabeth Gilbert

I’ve been applying this to my photography recently as it takes a weight off what should be a weightless form of expression. I would encourage you pursue your process in your creative medium!

This week my high school friends and I head off on our annual week long camping trip. This photo shows my tent from last years trip on the beach beneath the Milky Way and a hint of the northern lights in the distance. Last year we visited a few beaches on north most end of Vancouver island and this year we are heading out to a new spot which I’m excited to share once we are back! I’ve had this photo sitting in my drafts for a year now but figured this would be a fitting time to finally share it. There’s thousands of photos that have never seen the light of day😂

Portraits from Cambodia. My biggest tip for travel photographers is always to learn how to ask someone if you can take their photo in the local language. It’s an amazing way to start a conversation, meet a local and of course get amazing images.

Only 1.5 hours from Vancouver! Found the most beautiful lake overlooking these mountain tops. Spent a few days out here with @zoeakiko & @lil_niki camping in our matching Rav 4s overlooking this view. Such a great way to close out this summer season. Next stop 🍁🍂

Is this best creator camera on the market right now? If you want to see a full review on my YT channel let me know! I gotta be honest, I was skeptical when @canoncanada sent me this little guy to try out but it has really blown me away and I’ve used it daily since! You might not be shooting a movie (this would be a fun experiment though🤔) BUT when I’m heading out during the day or just wanna make a quick vlog / story I find myself grabbing this instead of my professional camera every time. It makes things so simple and I’ve found I’ve vlogged and captured more over the past few weeks because of that simplicity. Anything that helps me increase my creative output is a tool I’m going to keep in my toolkit. The v10 is here to stay for me but let me know your questions and thoughts in the comments so I can address them in future videos here and on YT! Love this little camera and used it to shoot this whole video!
Nothing beats spending all morning camping in a hammock next to a lake next to the mountains 🙌🏼

⬇️The most underrated solo filmmaking tool ⬇️ 
often, cinematic scenes don’t need elaborate setups, expensive gear or big crews. Sometimes, it’s just u, a tripod and a camera going for a walk.

🔸 **Composition & Lighting Mastery**: Sticking to still frames gives you the time to perfect your composition and find the best lighting. Without the complexity of movement, every frame becomes a canvas for you to paint with light and angles.

🔸 **Intentionality**: Shooting solo with a static frame forces you to be more intentional with each shot. It challenges your storytelling process, ensuring every second on screen matters. This is the same reason a lot of people like to take photos on film.

🔸 ** Observation**: In the stillness, you are able to observe more, find the beauty in simplicity and let your subject tell their story without any distractions.

Don’t be discourage by the flashy equipment and intricate techniques. Sometimes, all you need is a vision, and a tripod 🌟

Today marks three years of sharing life with this beautiful woman. Life has taken us to some pretty beautiful places and left us with beautiful memories to look back on. It feels like a million things have happened in just three years and I can’t wait to see what another three or even thirty brings on. The memories we have yet to make, the places we have yet to see, the challenges and the adventures. The highs and the lows are all a bit higher with you. You inspire me and push me to be a better version of myself daily. Happy 3 years @zoeakiko ❤️

Nothing makes me happier than experiencing a new culture through my photography. My camera has allowed me to meet so many incredible souls I would have never known otherwise. My camera has brought me around the globe and allowed me the privilege of learning and taking part in cultural experiences I’ve never even heard of in our western world. Every culture has stories to tell and I love finding faces that tell those stories without even needing words. There’s nothing that matches the connection you feel to a culture when looking down your lens into the eyes of your subject surrounded by the sounds, the smells and the atmosphere of a culture unlike anything you’ve grown up knowing. It’s incredible and I hope I’m not the only one who has experienced this or wants to. I believe it has the power to unite humans unlike anything else if you give it a chance.

Alone and lost in ancient temples. From one of my trips to south east Asia last year here are some frames I dug up from the archives from both Thailand and Cambodia. Incredible countries with incredible culture and history.

Instagram vs reality. This train ride from Bangkok to Chiang Mai was a roller coaster both physically and mentally. swipe to the last slide to hear my honest thoughts with @lexielimitless . The pain was worth it in the end for the amazing sunrise photoshoot we got but the 10 hours of night before it are among the top 10 worst sleeps I’ve had while traveling. That being said, once it was over it made for great laughs and good memories… would recommend👍🏼 just bring snacks, allergy medications, noise canceling headphone, a neck pillow and water.

As someone who has grown up in the rainiest part of North America  I would consider myself somewhat of a rain connoisseur, or a precipitation aficionado. I gotta say one of my favourite rainstorms I’ve ever experienced was under the thousand year old stone ceilings of Angkor Wat in Cambodia. Truly felt like a scene from Indiana Jones or Tomb Raider.

One of my favourite moments from our trip down the Baja near the beginning of this year. Wild horses who call this beach home wandering around and only attacking us once. These photos felt magical to capture as I sat in the shallow water observing these beautiful animals. My favourite moments as a photographer are ones like these where you have the chance to be present and both capture a moment on camera but also sit and take in the moment personally. Cannot wait to go back to the Baja soon… love all of our friends there and the memories we make every time we visit!

Found these photos in the archives from the first snow to hit Vancouver Island last year. Looking forward to more road-trips and adventures soon! Currently working hard to fix my back / lower spine problems which has meant stepping away from the more intensive travel and adventures for a while. It’s been a year of physiotherapy and I’m not seeing a ton of healing with has been rough. Hopefully I can get back out on the road soon and shoot some new photos. For now we will keep diving into the archives.

A simple frame from my first month in Bali back in 2019. Still can’t believe teenage me just sent it over to Bali without a clue of how to make it work. I am proud of that younger version of me for believing in himself and doing the uncomfortable to reach his goals. I want to make sure that in an another 4 or 5 years from now I feel the same towards myself today. Choosing the difficult path when there’s an easy one available is where growth begins.
Bali will always have a spot in my heart. The culture is so much richer than people often see and the people are so eager to share that culture with you. I have to go back sometime soon 🥹
Sometimes it’s the simple frames…
Tofino

3 tips that changed my edits⬇️
1. Always play around with your crop. Just because you composed your image a certain way when you shot it, doesn’t mean you can’t try out different options in the edit. A lot of these detail shots are heavily cropped in.
2. Use curves to edit instead of the shadows and highlights sliders. This one is for anyone using Lightroom. It may be faster to use the sliders and I still use them for big changes but to nail the right amount of contrast and to give the vintage, soft and smooth edit, it’s all in the way you use the curves . Usually it means creating a bit of and S with the curve line and lifting the bottom.
3. Master masking. Masks are your best friend in Lightroom because you can use them to adjust people and places on their own instead of changing the entire image. I use masks to often blur out the background more, remove the clarity from the ground, darken a corner or bottom of the frame. Masks help you choose which part of the frame you want to direct the attention to.

This trip to Raja back in March was too good to be true… it’s sad more people don’t get to enjoy this beautiful part of earth but that’s also what keeps it so beautiful. Still have so many photos I never posted from this boat.
Last few shots from Tofino! This place is magical. Just reminds me how bad I want some land on the coast here in bc one day…
Remembering warmer weather ☀️

social_posts.post_text: Mexico on film. Finally got some film developed from the past year so expect more film posts soon!

Having a camera on me at all times is less about “getting more photos” and more about constantly looking for beauty in the mundane. When you start looking for beauty in all things, the world becomes a more beautiful place.

In search of real moments…
My favourite photos will always be those that capture a person, a country or a culture in its most real and unfiltered form. Here is a moment from the islands of Indonesia when I was on the beach and a man leading 30+ cows with a cigarette in hand walked out of the bushes behind me. No setup, no lights, no posing, Just a moment captured and passed.

A frame from the Tokyo
Fun fact: I’ve been to Japan twice and filmed multiple vlogs there but never posted them because I wasn’t happy with how they turned out. Can’t tell you how many unseen vlogs live on my hard drives. Going back to Japan is high up on my list of travel goals for the near future.
